>>14018961
I'd say that greentexting comes with the expectation that the pace of the story will be a fast and the writing structured much like a list of bullet points. It skips over the conventions of long-form such as wordy descriptions and the like in favour of being easily readable.

I'm kind of split on whether I like writing in it or not, to be honest. I usually make my writing a toss-up of the two, writing sentences and dialogue as I usually would but breaking things up with the occasional meme arrow to make it more easy to digest. It's very much like using paragraphs, only more often.

>>14027883
If it was separating before the cheese then it could have also been overheating. Milk (and cheese) is of course partially composed of protein, and at a certain temperature those proteins will clump up and expel moisture, creating shitty little grains. For a good bechamel, cook a blonde roux (equal parts flour and butter in a pan for a few minutes until lightly fragrant) and then add cold (very important that there's a huge temperature difference between the two) milk. Whisk the shit out of it and bring it up to a simmer, and then back the heat down a bit until it's thickened the way you want.
